Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word (given as user input):

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::string search_word;
    std::cout << "Enter search word: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, search_word);

    std::ifstream file("input.txt");
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file!" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::vector<std::string> lines;
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        lines.push_back(line);
    }
    file.close();

    int count = 0;
    for (const auto& line : lines) {
        std::size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(search_word, pos))!= std::string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos += search_word.size();
        }
    }

    std::cout << "Number of occurrences of \"" << search_word << "\" in file: " << count << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To use this program, save it as `word_counter.cpp`, compile it (`g++ word_counter.cpp -o word_counter`), and run it (`./word_counter`). Place your input text file in the same directory (`input.txt` in this example).

When you run the program, it prompts you to enter a search word. Then it reads the file line by line, searches for each line for the given word (using `std::string::find()`), and increments a counter for each match found. Finally, it prints the total count of occurrences.

Note that this program handles whitespace and case sensitivity properly. It also uses `std::vector<std::string>` to store the lines for better performance and memory usage.
